WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.800
Mark it.

2
00:00:01.520 --> 00:00:02.399
- ...and set.
- Action.

3
00:00:02.799 --> 00:00:04.160
[hopeful piano music]

4
00:00:04.160 --> 00:00:05.480
I love working with new filmmakers.

5
00:00:05.480 --> 00:00:07.400
I love hearing their ideas

6
00:00:07.400 --> 00:00:09.599
and helping them find
a way to tell the stories

7
00:00:09.599 --> 00:00:10.800
that they want to tell.

8
00:00:11.320 --> 00:00:15.720
It's been quite a few months of
talking to not only Bus Stop students,

9
00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:18.239
also some great
industry professionals

10
00:00:18.239 --> 00:00:20.320
to talk to us about what they think

11
00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:22.480
are really important strategies

12
00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:24.640
for our students to be
able to be industry-ready.

13
00:00:24.640 --> 00:00:25.920
- Musicals.
- Musicals.

14
00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:26.519
[laughs]

15
00:00:27.640 --> 00:00:29.079
Going to PLACES, you're in

16
00:00:29.079 --> 00:00:31.320
just very small individual groups

17
00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:33.840
so you can have more
time with a professional

18
00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:37.399
and be able to learn
the particular subject.

19
00:00:37.399 --> 00:00:41.439
- This is slightly hands-on
actually doing something.

20
00:00:41.439 --> 00:00:44.039
CRAIG: Working in the little
silos of the camera team,

21
00:00:44.039 --> 00:00:46.520
and the directing team,
and the writing team

22
00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:49.560
was a great way for
people to really focus on

23
00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:51.880
the craft skills that
they wanted to develop.

24
00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:54.159
- Sometimes all three
would be together

25
00:00:54.159 --> 00:00:55.759
and then sometimes it would just be

26
00:00:55.759 --> 00:00:57.439
the directors and the camera team.

27
00:00:57.439 --> 00:00:59.119
- So we would have
these kind of periods

28
00:00:59.119 --> 00:01:00.359
where we would work separately

29
00:01:00.359 --> 00:01:02.200
but then we would come back together

30
00:01:02.200 --> 00:01:04.319
and we'd find new
things in that process.

31
00:01:04.319 --> 00:01:05.760
It was a nice way to work.

32
00:01:07.560 --> 00:01:10.519
From the start we're
just reading the scripts

33
00:01:10.519 --> 00:01:14.640
and giving some feedback to
how we understand the story

34
00:01:14.640 --> 00:01:17.079
and how we're going
to make it into a film.

35
00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:19.640
I remember when we got together

36
00:01:19.640 --> 00:01:21.319
with the other two streams,

37
00:01:21.319 --> 00:01:23.680
had a table read of the first draft.

38
00:01:23.680 --> 00:01:25.920
There were lots of
questions that people had.

39
00:01:27.519 --> 00:01:30.159
Hearing them defend their script

40
00:01:30.159 --> 00:01:34.359
and their work just made me
feel proud but also like,

41
00:01:34.359 --> 00:01:36.879
"Yes, this is a vibe!"

42
00:01:37.239 --> 00:01:37.920
"Love it."

43
00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:38.920
[laughs]

44
00:01:38.920 --> 00:01:41.840
- And it's not like, "we
can't use this idea at all."

45
00:01:41.840 --> 00:01:45.400
It's more like, "what we
can do to improve your idea."

46
00:01:45.879 --> 00:01:47.280
[clapping]

47
00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:48.560
[hopeful piano music ends]

48
00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:50.920
I don't know that I was
really teaching them that much.

49
00:01:50.920 --> 00:01:53.319
They all have watched
so much film and so much TV.

50
00:01:53.319 --> 00:01:56.280
They've already been
around so many things.

51
00:01:56.280 --> 00:01:58.079
They kind of all
know this stuff already.

52
00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:03.359
They all totally understand
the language of filmmaking.

53
00:02:03.359 --> 00:02:05.280
- ...Ideas, how we're gonna shoot,

54
00:02:05.280 --> 00:02:08.400
while we rehearsal with the script,

55
00:02:08.400 --> 00:02:10.400
come up with the shot ideas

56
00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:12.479
and how we're
gonna do it on the day.

57
00:02:12.680 --> 00:02:15.400
FATIMA: On the shoot,
the writing stream were

58
00:02:15.400 --> 00:02:17.479
the script supervisors.

59
00:02:17.479 --> 00:02:20.080
They watched the split
and had printed out versions

60
00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:22.520
of the script that they marked up.

61
00:02:23.039 --> 00:02:25.639
They learnt quite a
lot in that process as well,

62
00:02:25.639 --> 00:02:27.960
around the details
that you have to be noticing.

63
00:02:28.280 --> 00:02:30.000
A couple of scenes had to get cut

64
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.120
because they were
running low on time

65
00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:34.879
and they really felt like

66
00:02:34.879 --> 00:02:37.199
these were moments
that shouldn't be cut.

67
00:02:37.199 --> 00:02:41.080
And they were active around
finding Dianna, the producer,

68
00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:42.560
and vocalising

69
00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:45.199
why they felt like they
were important to be included.

70
00:02:45.479 --> 00:02:48.240
You write a script when you
write it, and you're writing it again

71
00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:49.120
when you're filming it, and then

72
00:02:49.120 --> 00:02:50.520
writing it again
when you're editing it.

73
00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:52.759
And I feel like
they really learnt that.

74
00:02:53.199 --> 00:02:55.599
The way the directing
stream worked was

75
00:02:55.599 --> 00:02:57.759
we looked at the
script and we carved it up.

76
00:02:57.759 --> 00:02:59.879
And you can kind of see the
hands of the directors

77
00:02:59.879 --> 00:03:00.680
on the different scenes,

78
00:03:00.680 --> 00:03:04.159
but the film does cohesively
sit together as a nice story.

79
00:03:04.919 --> 00:03:08.159
Because we did all these weeks,
we all read the script together.

80
00:03:08.159 --> 00:03:09.479
There was a lot of involvement,

81
00:03:09.479 --> 00:03:11.560
so by the time we
came to do the shoot,

82
00:03:11.560 --> 00:03:13.919
they knew exactly what the
shots were trying to do

83
00:03:13.919 --> 00:03:14.840
storytelling-wise.

84
00:03:15.159 --> 00:03:18.599
- I liked getting
hands-on with the camera.

85
00:03:18.919 --> 00:03:21.120
At least half of the shots
that are in the film

86
00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:23.159
are ones the
students are operating.

87
00:03:23.159 --> 00:03:24.479
- At first I was a bit nervous,

88
00:03:24.479 --> 00:03:26.800
but once I knew there
were people around me,

89
00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:29.319
if I needed help, I
could always turn to them.

90
00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:32.120
We'd spent time in class
discussing headroom

91
00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:33.719
and where the people are,

92
00:03:33.719 --> 00:03:36.039
and they all took all that on board

93
00:03:36.039 --> 00:03:37.639
on the set, and
that worked really well.

94
00:03:37.639 --> 00:03:38.800
[stirring piano music]

95
00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:41.400
It was a full heart moment
watching them on set,

96
00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:44.039
watching them feel confident
to work with the actors

97
00:03:44.039 --> 00:03:46.080
and still hold
true to their visions.

98
00:03:47.080 --> 00:03:49.800
SAMIRA: Telling the actors
what they needed to do

99
00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:52.000
and telling the camera what shot.

100
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:52.919
- It was fantastic.

101
00:03:56.319 --> 00:03:59.280
Bus Stop allowed
enough of a structure

102
00:03:59.280 --> 00:04:03.759
but left flexibility so
that you can tailor

103
00:04:03.759 --> 00:04:06.639
your class to what
they're interested in.

104
00:04:06.639 --> 00:04:08.479
- They're learning
what they want to learn.

105
00:04:08.479 --> 00:04:09.960
CRAIG: They really pushed themselves

106
00:04:09.960 --> 00:04:12.439
to do something that
they wanted to watch.

107
00:04:12.439 --> 00:04:14.080
The results far exceeded

108
00:04:14.080 --> 00:04:15.639
anything I thought
we were going to create.

109
00:04:16.199 --> 00:04:18.759
Everyone who was in our team

110
00:04:18.759 --> 00:04:21.079
really came out of their shells
the more that we worked together.

111
00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:23.480
They've definitely
grown in confidence.

112
00:04:23.759 --> 00:04:28.480
FATIMA: Seeing them grow to further
their creative development has,

113
00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:31.079
in what seems to be
a horrible world right now,

114
00:04:31.079 --> 00:04:33.199
makes you feel a bit warm and fuzzy.

115
00:04:33.879 --> 00:04:37.920
MARCUS: Not easy to make a film or
like to write a script on your own.

116
00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:39.759
I think I should put myself
out there more

117
00:04:39.759 --> 00:04:42.639
and find people to work along with.

118
00:04:43.160 --> 00:04:45.879
Even anything trying to stop you,

119
00:04:45.879 --> 00:04:49.079
you just block them and just
go for what you love to do.

120
00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:53.839
- More and more experiences,
as you get more hours in.

121
00:04:54.160 --> 00:04:57.160
Everything I learnt down here
I know is going to pay off someday.

122
00:04:57.439 --> 00:04:59.800
I'm just really happy that
they've got something out of it.

123
00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:03.360
- PLACES now really
gives that next step up.

124
00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:06.560
- It's a great way to transition
to mainstream filmmaking.

125
00:05:06.879 --> 00:05:08.800
I just want PLACES to go on forever.

126
00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:10.959
CRAIG: This industry
can have a lot of closed doors

127
00:05:10.959 --> 00:05:13.639
to people who are underrepresented

128
00:05:13.639 --> 00:05:15.319
and we miss out
on hearing those stories

129
00:05:15.319 --> 00:05:17.800
if we don't have pathways
for those people.

130
00:05:17.800 --> 00:05:19.199
That's a wrap!

131
00:05:19.199 --> 00:05:20.279
- That's a wrap people.

132
00:05:22.079 --> 00:05:24.120
[clapping &amp; cheering]

133
00:05:24.120 --> 00:05:26.800
Well done everyone,
thank you so much.

